NSA case highlights total lack of intelligence debate
How to explain the contradictory attitude of the French government, which on the one hand is offended in public by summoning the ambassador of the United States on October 21, and on the other, prohibits the overflight of the territory by the Bolivian presidential plane, on the basis of the rumor of the presence on board of Edward Snowden?
In my opinion, there are two levels of response from the French government.
When François Hollande calls Barack Obama or when Foreign Minister Laurent Fabius summons the U.S. ambassador, they react to a real discovery, which is the extent of American surveillance on all communications in France.
Is it not surprising to read in the columns of Le Monde a few weeks apart on the one hand the reproduction of the American diplomatic correspondence and on the other hand a condemnation of the listenings of the Quai d'Orsay by the NSA?
Wouldn't there be like a vague hypocrisy on your part?
The journalistic approach is not a moral position, but the search for the interest and relevance of information that allows each citizen to forge an opinion.
When WikiLeaks lifts the veil on the analysis by American diplomacy of political or other issues around the world, we consider that, in the light of American power, this is an important insight.
When we describe American interception systems against French diplomacy in the United States, it is in no way to be outraged by this practice, it is to describe the world as it is.
Has France benefited from information provided by the NSA regarding terrorist operations targeting our interests?
Can we deprive ourselves of American collaboration?
The implementation of technological tools of very powerful interception by the United States, but also by France, for the past ten years, has been officially justified by the fight against terrorism.
Moreover, in this area, France and the United States in particular have established procedures for cooperation and exchange of information that are almost daily and which are described on both sides as essential.
For example, the presence of Mohammed Merah in the tribal areas of Miranshah was reported to the French thanks to the NSA’s means.
France can be led, for example, to transmit entire blocks of data on the Sahel region to American services, and, in return - as has already been said - the Americans can give information to the French on other regions of the world.
So the substantive question behind this NSA case is not so much the capacity or the right of countries to equip themselves with interception tools, as the question of the total absence of prior debate, especially in Parliaments, on the justification of such systems, the perimeter that must be their own, and, ultimately, the question of infringements of freedoms.
What is the real risk of the United States? a deterioration of its image?
We may denounce them, but I don't see how they can be punished.
The risk faced by the Americans can be twofold.
The first is when their allies – and recently – learn that their leaders, sometimes at the highest peak of their state, have been monitored.
This is the case in Brazil and Germany, two countries where diplomatic relations with the United States have been strained.
Another effect may be more economical: more and more European or South American companies are reluctant, in the light of the revelations, to entrust their confidential data to American service providers subject to American laws, and therefore to the control of the NSA.
Last element: the broad movement of revelations initiated by media around the world, which helps to initiate a debate on the surveillance practices of the intelligence services hitherto virtually non-existent, could push lawmakers, including the American, to reconsider the powers they have given to their intelligence services.
