New anti-nicotine vaccine could suppress the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could suppress the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
Only one dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice for life from nicotine addiction.
Further tests are needed before starting human trials, but Professor Ronald Crystal of the Weill Cornell Medical College in New York City said the first signs were encouraging.
“We really hope that this kind of vaccine strategy can help millions of smokers who have tried to quit, exhausting all the methods available on the market today, but discover that their addiction is strong enough to overcome these different approaches,” said Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to carry the genetic information needed to design anti-nicotin antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begins to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies track down all the nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from having his dose of nicotine.
During the tests, the vaccinated mice who were then given nicotine continued their activity normally.
But mice that had not been vaccinated “were calmed,” the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have proven to be ineffective because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be repeated so frequently so that the antibody levels remained high that they were too expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine should be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human-use vaccine was completely safe, it could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, which would prevent any nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely to be used by smokers who want to quit smoking.
“They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not enjoy it because of the nicotine vaccine, and it can help them lose their bad habit,” he added.
British scientists said the findings were interesting but reported that much more in-depth research was needed.
