FAA: Air passengers can now use gadgets on board airplanes (but not make a call with their mobile phone)
Airlines passengers will be able to use their door-to-door electronic devices to read, work, play games, watch movies, and listen to music — but not talk on their mobile phones — under the much-anticipated new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers should not expect immediate changes.
The speed with which the change will be implemented will vary from airline to airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a press conference.
Airlines will have to prove to the FAA that their aircraft comply with the new guidelines and have updated the crew training manuals and the rules for the storage of aircraft to be in compliance.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of electronic devices on their aircraft.
Delta and JetBlue are among the companies that have already submitted plans.
“Depending on the plan, we could approve a broader use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers must turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not supposed to turn them back on until the plane reaches an altitude of 10 000 feet and the commander gives the green light.
Passengers are expected to turn off their aircraft when the aircraft descends before landing and not turn them back on until the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference will be able to allow passengers to use their aircraft during take-offs, landings and ground running, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified so that passengers can use Wi-Fi at higher altitudes, should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Flight Attendants, said she was pleased with these changes.
“Once the new policy is implemented safely – and we will work closely with the carriers for that – it will benefit everyone,” Glading said in a statement.
We are frankly tired of feeling like "room supervisors" when it comes to this issue.
But it will still be forbidden to connect to the Internet to surf, exchange emails and SMS or download data below 10 000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will have to put their smartphones, tablets and other devices in airplane mode.
So still no Words With Friends, the online game Scrabble style that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011 when he was thrown out loudly from an American Airlines plane after refusing to turn off his device while the aircraft was parked at the door.
And heavier devices like laptops will still have to be stored because they could hurt someone if they flew through the cabin.
Mobile phones on board will also continue to be banned.
The regulatory power over mobile phones is part of the Federal Communications Commission and not the FAA.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert on CBS News, said mobile phones are still considered to be at risk.
“Mobile phones are truly a problem, not only because they could eventually create interference with navigational instruments, but because we know, according to the FCC, that they could disrupt mobile phone relay antennas if used on board,” Rosenker said.
An industrial advisory committee set up by the FAA to examine the issue recommended last month that the government allow for wider use of personal electronic devices.
The pressure on the FAA has increased in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Senator Claire McCaskill, D-Mo., argue that there is no valid security reason for these prohibitions.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because device use has become ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that at least one-third of passengers forget to turn off their devices, or do so deliberately.
The FAA began to limit the use of electronic devices in 1996 following reports of interference with navigation and communication instruments when passengers were carrying FM radios, the then high-tech gadget.
New airliners depend much more on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed to withstand electronic and FAA-approved interference.
Airlines have allowed their passengers to use Wi-Fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Aircraft modified to accommodate Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airliners are expected to allow for wider use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit radio transmissions of much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, only issue minimal transmissions when turning a page.
But transmissions are stronger when devices download or send data.
Amazon.com is among those pushing for a relaxation of restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers.
In 2011, the company’s executives loaded an airliner with Kindle e-book readers and flew it to see if there were any problems, but there were none.
This inspired the members of the FAA Advisory Committee on mixed feelings about whether or not the use of the devices poses a risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believed interference from the aircraft was real, even though the risk was minimal.
Other members of the committee said that there are only anecdotal reports from pilots that indicate that aircraft can interfere with an aircraft’s systems, and that most of them are very old.
However, the Committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to request passengers to turn off their aircraft during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A group in the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling for common-sense arrangements for technology-equipped travellers.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that an enjoyable passenger experience is not incompatible with safety,” said Roger Dow, President and Director of the U.S. Travel Association.
The rules on the use of electronic devices on board remain in force in Australia for the time being
Australian air passengers will have to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing despite the US gesture of relaxing electronic device regulations.
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration has left the door open for U.S. carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos, or play games on their devices during critical flight phases provided they are in “aircraft” mode.
Passengers can already do this for most of the flight, but many people find it difficult not to be able to access their e-books during take-off and landing.
Australian carriers are reviewing the decision requiring U.S. carriers to perform significant work to meet the requirements, but indicated that they do not immediately intend to change their procedures.
The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also said it was reviewing the announcement but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical flight phases were still in effect in Australia.
“CASA does not have specific regulations governing the use of electronic devices on an airplane,” she said.
The issue is subject to regulation requiring aircraft operators to ensure that safety is maintained on a permanent basis and for passengers to comply with the safety instructions given by crew members.
Virgin, who has previously spoken to CASA about her intention to expand the use of her on-board entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology, was open to change, but said she would follow the regulator.
“We would welcome a revision of CASA that would allow the use of electronic devices because we truly believe that it would improve the customer experience now that we have (the onboard entertainment system using Wi-Fi technology) on our aircraft,” a spokesperson said.
Qantas said she is following the current rules for the time being.
“In keeping with our current policy, electronic devices cannot be used during take-off and landing, and we do not immediately intend to change that,” she said.
The FAA decision applies to U.S. airlines.
However, we are still interested in regulatory developments that could benefit passengers, and we will take a close look at the FAA’s decision and the reasons for it.
For U.S. carriers, the impact of the decision will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will be required to demonstrate that their aircraft can tolerate radio interference from electronic devices, as well as review manuals, training equipment, carry-on baggage programs and passenger instructions.
“As soon as an airline has verified the tolerance of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use lightweight portable electronic devices, such as tablets, e-book readers and smartphones at all altitudes,” the FAA said.
In the rare cases of low visibility, the crew will ask passengers to turn off their aircraft during landing.
The group also recommended that heavier aircraft be safely stored under the seats or in the upper compartments during take-off and landing.
