“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him abroad if we had had enough money.
Instead, Dr. Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to crowded clinics and hospitals, so that he would get any treatment he could get.
“It’s not easy,” Mr. adds. Bwelle.
You can leave the house at 5 a.m., rush to the hospital to be the first, and you are not the first.
There are many patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since the death of Dr. Bwelle's father in 2002.
In Cameroon, there are only 1 doctor per 5 000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
For comparison, the ratio in the United States is 1 physician for 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line, and almost three-quarters of the country’s health spending is in the private sector.
“The only problem they have is poverty,” Dr. Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and so many of his compatriots suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers have practiced more than 700 surgical procedures free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at Yaoundé Central Hospital.
And he has created a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas over the weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32 000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about thirty people, they pile up in vans after fixing the medical equipment on the roof and crossing difficult terrain to get to the villages that need the most help.
Luck doesn't always follow them.
They have repeatedly had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
But when they arrive, they are received as a hero: the community organizes a party, sings and dances and offers them the best accommodations available.
In these villages, free health care is a good reason to party, and Dr. Bwelle – with his big smile and overflowing energy – is more than happy to join the festivities.
The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
“We get 500 people on each visit,” Mr. said. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this homeless hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, a pair of glasses collected, or a free birth certificate – a document needed to go to school, but many poor families simply can’t afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practices simple surgical procedures under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually performed in a school, a town hall or a house; after the intervention, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery room to leave his place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a grueling rhythm, but the musicians of the villages generally help the team to stay motivated.
“They hit drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working,” Mr. explained. Bwelle.
On Sundays, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work they have done.
The group, made up of Cameroonian physicians and medical students, has performed 700 surgical procedures free of charge over the past year, and it knows that their presence can make all the difference for those they help.
A man explained that the free operation he had undergone to treat a hernia would allow him to work again.
“This will change my future and that of my family,” the man said.
In addition to supporting this itinerant hospital and working as a surgeon in the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at night in private medical offices around Yaoundé.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances 60% of its association; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don’t know when he’s sleeping,” said Katie O’Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer with Dr. Bwelle’s group.
He is still in the hospital or trying to find money for his association so he can run these campaigns.
For medical students and nursing students like Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join M. Bwelle in his missions, it's a learning opportunity in the field that they don't have at home.
"We were able to participate in operations to help sponge blood or pass the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," said O'Malley.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a second year medical student.
Volunteer students generally pay for their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transport and teaching are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
“He’s a hero, there’s no doubt,” said Katie O’Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not about to die out.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a difficulty.
Helping others to live happily by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him immense joy.
“I’m so happy when I do this work,” added Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Making people laugh and relieve pain are the reasons why I do this.
