“Everyone can soon be identified, anywhere and anytime,” said Justin Brookman, head of consumer privacy at the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in some, and pessimism, in others?
Biometrics will be based on new techniques, which will make it possible to provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, the contour of the hand and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
“For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are illegible,” says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand presuppose a voluntary and precise gesture of the people.
It is both a security - we can not capture this data without their knowledge - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore takes time.
As a result, research has been conducted over the past twenty years on other approaches, such as facial or iris recognition (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increase in sensor accuracy and computing capacity of computers necessary for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has increased tenfold over the past five years, says Cyrille Bataller, director of Accenture’s R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the UK and Holland have deployed automatic border crossings using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a face or a moving iris.
“Today, we’re conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk using sound sensors, but we need a silent environment,” said Sridhar Iyengar, director of security research at the Intel Labs.
A unique and unfalsifiable marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, director of studies, innovation and foresight at the CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police services a suitcase costing 90,000 euros to analyze DNA samples at the scene of a crime and in one hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (ensuring that the person is the one they claim to be).
The identification until now concerned the issuance of identity documents: it is necessary to confront the biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) with the information that the State has on all the citizens already registered.
This ensures that a person does not try to impersonate someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a shop.
“We collect images from surveillance cameras and compare them to photos of celebrities who circulate freely on the Internet,” says Dany Nassif, head of business development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other use: take a picture of a quidam who queues in a store, track his progress through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially concerned physical access (borders, protected premises, canteens, etc.) or logical access (opening of a computer).
More recently, attendance control was added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the friend who points for another," justifies Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But, more and more, authentication will also concern transactions, especially those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing his card and putting his hand on a biometric reader: this gesture replaces the striking of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the company Natural Security in partnership with banks and retailers: when paying in store with his credit card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger in a reader who scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
