Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog’s tail are related to his mood.
Previous studies had found that happy dogs moved their tails further to the right (from the dog’s point of view), while nervous dogs moved them further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: “Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved in a different way in stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions. »
Here we tried to see what was happening in other species.
He added that just as in humans, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs respond to the disordered tail movements of other dogs, the researchers tracked animals watching movies where other dogs were featured.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
It will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: “We presented dogs with films featuring other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confounding factors – and we were able to traffic the movement of the tail and present it as going further to the left or right. »
When the animals saw a dog without expression wagging the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog wagging the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail deviating mainly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: “If you repeatedly encounter other dogs and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tail to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react based on that experience. »
The researchers indicate that the findings could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
Canine behavioral expert John Bradshaw, a visiting professor at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Science, said this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they were looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when it was a cheerful dog.
And in another scientific study conducted by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: “Dogs would more easily go to a robot dog when its tail was moving to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious — the opposite of what’s in the Italian study. »
He said the differences could come from the fact that the dogs that participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of the movies or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“Although many elements, found in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviors can be recorded, it will surely not be long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
