Early Puberty : Ageing Earlier
Studies show that African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
Physical changes do not mean that puberty is imminent
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe the obesity epidemic could be a trigger for early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is not as pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in family and health issues in children.
Should a mother worry if her daughter’s bristles and pubic hair start growing at age 7 or 8?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, the pedo-endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among young American women and represent a new standard.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – in general, it doesn’t indicate a rapid shift towards full puberty,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as breast budding, hair under the arms and in the pubic area and body odors, appear earlier in girls.
But there has been only a slight advance in the age of the first few periods in the last four decades.
In the United States, the average age is 12 and a half years, when it was 12 years three-quarters in 1970.
“Once the chest has started to develop, it takes at least two or three years before the first periods appear,” said Kaplowitz, also the author of “Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.”
Time is the most accurate test to find out how puberty will evolve.
There is a debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but it is considered "early" when the development of the chest is accompanied by sudden growth before the age of 8.
In most cases, development slows down or stops – it’s something a pediatrician can follow closely.
A faster evolution can justify tests performed by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay the appearance of the first period and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones that can slow growth and a small size in adulthood.
Drug and hormonal treatment recommendations are based on the age of the child, developmental rate, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with the drugs but acknowledges that “controlling puberty can alleviate some behavioral problems and the feeling for young girls to be different from others.”
The other big problem is understandable: Parents simply don’t want their very young girls to have their period.
“They fear the risk of pregnancy or even the way they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls a woman whose daughter had her first period at 10.
Even though there were signs and we talked about the rules, she wasn’t emotionally prepared.
She came home from school scared and upset to be the first among her friends.
There are many theories brought to the public's knowledge about the causes of early puberty.
Yet there is no consistent theory that hormones contained in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages conveyed by the media are responsible.
Boys, like girls, reach their puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz claims that the most credible hypothesis is that of the obesity epidemic.
He participated in a study conducted on girls aged 6 to 9 years who link the percentage of fat mass to the triggering of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other influential factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty age earlier than white girls.
There are various explanations.
Globally, the mechanisms of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another problem: Although boys have hair on their face and in the younger pubic area, the trend towards genuine early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the PAA conference emphasized the complexity of the topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common, even in infants and toddlers.
“We need to be careful about how we identify the true appearance of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, a child endocrinologist working at Goryeb Children’s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to ask their pediatrician for advice on how to talk to their child.
“It may mean having a conversation sooner than expected,” Kaplowitz said.
If you stay calm, your child will generally react well.
Girls with early puberty should be reassured that even when it happens sooner than expected, the process is part of life.
