Here is the real news about Europe: the great post-war plan to unify Europe is definitely at a standstill.
With the euro crisis, Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties that oppose the EU or campaign for the abandonment of the euro as a common currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Alternative for Germany Eurosceptic Party, founded only this year and arrived out of nowhere, gathered almost five million votes in the September federal election and took the Liberal Democratic Party (equivalent to our Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been national opposition to the project of creating a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has marked a turning point.
The austerity imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, coupled with the straitjacket on national economies through membership of the single currency, has led many people to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments with excessive budget deficits – this was only true for Greece.
Instead, the European system has placed favourable exchange rates on its members for German exporters – something German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of a devaluation of the national currency, the countries of southern Europe find themselves with a problem of intrinsic productivity vis-à-vis Germany.
The only recourse is to make dark cuts in public wages and spending – encouraged by Berlin.
Beyond the current fiscal and monetary problems, there is a deeper productivity-related malaise in Europe.
Following the “green” energy policies imposed by Brussels – which are a reason to subsidize French and German energy companies at consumer cost – European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times more for gas than the United States.
This is a prohibitive cost disadvantage, as we have already seen in Grangemouth.
Not all wage freezes in the world will prevent the European petrochemical industry from being penalized by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, the revolt is rumbling, especially in France, one of the great leaders of the EU.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on an equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a passport to its political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy in Europe, leaving the French economy struggling to struggle.
The result: Marine Le Pen’s far-right party, the Anti-European National Front, has just won a crucial by-election, returning the ruling socialists to third place.
