A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York has identified a new species of humpback dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, scientific mission officer at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Environments (OCEAMM) returns for L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identification of new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of humpback dolphin surprise you?
This is good news, but it does not surprise me particularly.
If in the past, the species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allow us to improve our knowledge of species classification sciences.
Moreover, it is not impossible that these advances in genetics and molecular biology will call into question the classification or the belonging of a species to a genus, a family, or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals, based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these rankings are being challenged because of advances in genetics.
Similarly, two very morphologically close species were distinguished through genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
A decade ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific humpback dolphins and Atlantic humpback whales.
Recent analyses have distinguished four species.
Why is this a major discovery, as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation perspective, it is essential to know these genetic differences, in order to protect the species and therefore its genetic variability.
If this population had already been known to researchers for a long time, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only there.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture arises in the region, we could be dealing with the extinction of a species, rather than the local disappearance of a population of a species that is more widespread on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered threatened or endangered based on the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. the stock, and the ability it has to recover from nearby stocks.
For the species Sousa chinensis, from which the population of the new discovery species originated, its stock has automatically become lower, thus making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats, in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene mixing limits the creation of new species.
Conversely, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
The marine environment is the least well-known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars than to know what lives in the Mariana Trench, just 11 kilometers from the surface of the sea.
More money is spent on the search for life on other planets than in marine research, and it is high time for this to change.
