Two YMCA employees charged with sexual assault following allegations made against Jonathan Lord at a hearing of the Royal Commission.
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales were charged with sexual assault against children following allegations made against Caringbah educator Jonathan Lord in 2011 at a hearing of the Royal Commission on Sexual Abuse of Children.
But in its opening statement to the Commission, the YMCA said it “never had to deal with a problem of sexual assault on children within its organization.”
Director General Phillip Hare was questioned about two cases: a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences and a physical education monitor at the YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sexual assault on children in the centre where he worked in 1991.
M. Hare told Gail Furness, a counsel to the Board, that he had knowledge of the first case but was not aware of the second.
He also admitted that the YMCA opening statement was inaccurate, noting, “External controls of the YMCA have been carried out and have indicated that child safety is a top priority for the organization. »
The Commission was shown to have been informed that it received the second worst assessments in four institutions during a quality audit by the Department of Education and Communities conducted in August this year.
M. Hare, who started working at the YMCA at the age of 21, admitted that the management of staff was a failure with Lord's recruitment and that he had failed to verify that employees knew they were required to report any violations of the child safety policy.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexual assault on twelve boys during the two years he worked at the YMCA.
He was sentenced to a minimum of 6 years in prison.
But M. Hare rejected the idea that the YMCA has a cultural problem preventing staff from reporting Lord's failures toward child safety.
Staff members testified that they had observed certain shortcomings, including the fact that Lord was left alone with the children, kept them in private, had them sit on his knees, told them that he loved them and let them play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was supervised by Lord and had requested training in child protection because she was concerned about her behaviour, said she found the YMCA Caringbah's head of children's services, Jacqui Barnat, who was supervising Lord "very intimidating and difficult to approach most of the time."
The Director General said that he rejected the staff's testimony that they were reluctant to report these breaches to their supervisor.
Instead, he stated that the friendly relationship they had with Lord blurred their judgment, so they did not report his actions.
M. Hare said he had expressed his views before the YMCA council in New South Wales that, for the organization, the lesson learned from the "Jonaton Lord incident" should not concern "the report" by the staff, and the council agreed with him.
M. Hare said the decision to have staff sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations were raised was made by YMCA Director General for Child Services Liam Whitley.
He stated that this decision was intended to avoid any contamination of the evidence but that it was an "overzeal" and that it had been poorly implemented.
The YMCA of New South Wales was not a safe organization for children at the time Jonathan Lord was employed there, from 2009 to 2011, the expert on sexual violence against children, Professor Stephen Smallbone of the University of Griffith told the Commission.
He indicated that there were "serious problems" in recruiting, controlling, initiating, training and supervision of staff.
The hearing was adjourned until December 20.
A ceremony in memory of the dead crematized
The crematorium of Father Lachaise organizes, at 11 a.m., a secular ceremony, in memory of all the deceased crematized in his establishment, during the year.
Anne Hidalgo, socialist candidate for mayor of Paris must attend, and will then explain, at a press conference, her proposals in the field of funeral.
To follow the ceremony, click above.
For their own funerals, more and more French people choose cremation, rather than burial: 53%, according to an Ipsos study carried out on September 6 and 7 among 1009 people, instead of 47%.
For the funeral of a loved one, it is the opposite: the French prefer burial (53% against 47%).
If they have the misfortune of losing a child, they are only 15% to choose cremation.
In his book Death in Ashes, Damien Le Guay, philosopher and vice-president of the National Committee on the Ethics of the Funeral, insists on the "violence" that constitutes cremation, for the survivors.
There is, with cremation, "a violence done to the beloved body", which will be "reduced to a pile of ashes" in a very short time, and not after a process of decomposition, which would "accompany the phases of mourning".
There is also "symbolic violence", which is due to the "erasure of the singularity and distinctive signs" reduced to the "anonymity" of the ashes.
Why is what is accepted without difficulty in some Nordic and Protestant countries still badly experienced in France?
"Because cremation is a new fact," replies Marie-Frédérique Bacqué, president of the Société de thanatologie and author of the book Taming Death.
It has only been tolerated since 1963 by the Catholic Church, which has limited attempts to tame it.
To tame cremation is for François Michaud-Nérard, director general of the Funeral Services of the City of Paris, to provide for the deceased a ceremony as dignified as that to which he would be entitled with a burial.
The annual survey of Ipsos shows a very strong attachment to the organization of the ceremony.
77% of French people want one, for their relatives, whether religious (53%), or civil (24%).
Now, 73% of people who have chosen a cremation want to organize a ceremony.
66% of atheists or non-believers also want it.
The crematoriums have adapted to this evolution of society.
"For a decade, they have been trying to avoid the violence of a wait, without doing anything, for an hour and a half, immediately followed by the remission of the ashes," observes Mr. Michaud-Nérard.
70% of the establishments now offer masters of ceremonies, who proceed, in the presence of the body, to the following ritual: to welcome the assembly, to name the deceased, to connect him to the others, to evoke him, to give meaning to his death, to organize the farewell.
This is the case at the crematorium of Father Lachaise, since 1998.
Masters of ceremonies are often people who have converted.
There are also ancient Catholic priests.
It is in this context that the crematorium of Père Lachaise organizes, since 2010, the day of La Toussaint, several ceremonies of remembrance, lay and non-religious, to which it invites the families of the people who were crematized in the year.
For the second year in a row, one of these ceremonies is broadcast online, to the attention of those who could not make the trip.
The crematorium allowed us to relay it.
