Back in black and white for Marie Chouinard, who presents at Danse Danse her two new group choreographies: the first inspired by the inks and poems of Henri Michaux, the second infused by the famous piano solos Gymnopedias of Satie.
An evening that allows you to see all the prism of Chouinard, from art to tics and from ink black to white.
A white screen serves as a background wall.
On the carpet, also white, in the immense space that is the Théâtre Maisonneuve, advances, in profile, thin like a line and dressed in black, a body.
On the screen, an ink by Henri Michaux is projected.
The body, simple stroke, takes its shape.
And this shape will be that of the whole room: a string of physical imitations of the drawings.
The dancers, fully dressed in black, only the hands and face uncovered, wait on each side of the playground, rush when the next graph appears, embody it, emerge while running.
This black and white game by Henri Michaux is made in relays of solos, in group in unison (a mass that makes solo), in large group of twelve solos where each performs his sign.
We think of "Gloire du matin", where, solo, Chouinard was performing a series of choreographic tasks written on cartels, posed online at the forefront.
It's the same principle, giant PowerPoint version.
Here, the music is loud, percussion and electric guitars.
The energy is high, the pace always fast.
There will be a break when Carol Prieur takes refuge under the dance rug, to deliver, microphone in hand, without sobriety or restraint, a part of the poem of Michaux, monochord and monotonous in the scream, and continue dancing.
And the music to leave, and the sequence to resume.
This sound and energetic discharge, long, if it can, ends up deafening and numb.
As is also the regularity of the visual rhythm.
There are some beautiful flashes - the creation of images has always been a strength in Chouinard - like this hair that ruffles or these black fabrics that lengthen the lines.
But the choreographic approach lacks composition.
We have the impression that the choreographer, instead of going to meet the work of Michaux, imposed herself, with her tics.
The result: the bodies seem flat in front of the drawings.
Michaux's inks, like Gestalt forms, open a wider and giboed imagination than dance, more porous.
Only the end, in negative, with its dancers chopped by a strobe light and the white signs in a suddenly black theater, touches magic.
The public loved it, the welcome was warm.
Gymnopedias, after the intermission, is richer.
The scene is partly draped in gray, the dancers and a piano are covered with fabrics, like furniture in an abandoned house.
On the piano, dancers take turns playing the scores.
Their awkwardness in music, touching, gives a real fragility.
On stage, pass the couples, in love duos, very sensual, even erotic.
Group work, small transition solos, moving sets, choirs, writing is less binary.
Buffoons appear, also familiar with Chouinard, sporting the red nose, in very polarized male-female parades.
Loves are carnivoists, fleeing or players.
The gestures, the laughter and the little cries beautifully transpose the archaic, the grace and the ridicule of the bodies into coitus, beings that blend.
But the play takes off its real flight after salvation.
A clown comes back on the scene when the audience leaves.
There, everything becomes permissible: the fourth wall falls, the explored universes are superimposed, the dancers cabotine, descend among the spectators, gloss, smoke, short-circuit, play the codes of applause, stretch the sauce in a cleverly calculated disorder that remains sensual.
Joy and madness sweat, and it's the art of Chouinard, there, to contaminate the public.
