Is the European elite ready to do business with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of bringing businesses together and defining what wealth and job creators want to change in our relationship with the EU.
To do this, we commissioned the broadest and most comprehensive survey of UK business leaders and asked them what they thought of Britain, business and the EU.
YouGov surveyed more than 1 000 business leaders, broadly representative of all sizes of companies, sectors and regions of Great Britain.
The findings of the investigation will be a surprise to many.
We have discovered that the vast majority of companies are now looking to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernizing and developing while EU states are stagnating.
They want the government to prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India and Brazil rather than getting bogged down in the long and arduous process of reforming European institutional arcana.
When asked for their opinion on specific policy issues – ranging from the regulation of monopolies to product laws – the majority of business leaders believe that controlling these key competencies should return to Westminster’s hands.
The single market has caused general dissatisfaction, with companies saying that the cost of the Brussels regulation is disproportionate to the benefits of being part of the European trade area – 40% of the large companies, traditionally the most pro-European, even agree.
Finally, and what is even more telling, our survey of business leaders revealed that a large majority want to see Britain continue initiatives to change the treaty and develop a trade-based relationship with the EU, not politics.
This conclusion, which is found in all major groups and companies of all sizes, shows that the corporate world insists on a “significant change” that gives power back to the UK.
The stakes are high – succeeding in changing the treaty and better representing Britain’s interests would allow for a 16% shift in votes in favour of keeping the country in the EU in a referendum.
The Prime Minister should not doubt for a moment: this survey shows that British companies support this plan to renegotiate the terms of Britain's accession to the EU.
