Paying on jewelry is not only a quick way to get cash – $1 300 from Singapore in the case of Ms. Amirthalinga – but it’s almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
In general, Singapore's pawnshops charge an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4% offered by United Overseas Bank, a local funder with a branch in the same shopping centre.
However, pawnshops have the advantage of not seeking credit checks or proof of salary, and can unlock loans faster than banks.
As a result, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops as families feel the pressure of rising costs of living and over-indebtedness in households and consumers.
After five years of solid growth since the global financial crisis, and cheap credit fueled by too lax monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to make up for the difference as their economies slow down.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's cited growing household debt, stemming mainly from rising mortgages, as a risk factor for the solvency of Asian banks.
It said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore had the highest ratio of household debt to gross domestic product in Asia.
Malaysia topped the list with 80% of GDP, while the rate stood at 60% in 2008.
Economists are also concerned about the high level of consumer debt in Thailand, which this week came out of a technical recession.
On Thursday, data showed continued low exports and a slowdown in consumer demand.
“The balance sheet is that with rising costs, people in the middle or bottom [of the wage scale] are looking to supplement their income as they can,” says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historically high gold prices over the past two years have made people rush to pledge their personal belongings to receive the cash value of their jewelry.
In Singapore, about 70% of the items pledged in the city-state’s 200 pay-on-pay shops are gold.
People say, "The price of gold is high, let's pawn the grandmother's gold chain and we'll come back to get it next month."
In Thailand, the largest operator of pawnshop shops, EasyMoney, has seen a 20% increase in the number of customers using its stores in recent months.
The rise is such in the pawnshop industry that ValueMax, the store’s operator in Bendemeer and 15 other stores like this in Singapore, plans to expand not only in neighboring Malaysia – where it already has four stores – but also outside Asia, says Yeah Lee Ching, its managing director.
The company will fund them using 60% of Singapore’s 66 million dollars it raised this week when it was IPO of the Singapore Stock Exchange.
While some low-rate lenders have come under criticism for the exorbitant interest rates they practice, Miss Yeah indicates that the pledge not only offers lower rates than other lenders, but also does not directly increase debt.
“Customers mortgage property they already own, and monetizing their personal property does not increase household debt,” she says.
Pawning is increasingly socially accepted as a means of obtaining short-term guaranteed financing.
The people who go to the pawnshops are also not just those who have financial problems.
Affluent Singaporeans also go to ValueMax pledge shops to pawn gold bars or Rolex watches, which can account for up to 60% of their cash purchase price.
We see clients from all walks of life.
“It can be wealthy people who need to borrow in the short term for business or investment, or small businesses that have cash flow needs to take a difficult course,” adds Ms. Yeah.
